<paragraph id="355ED367FF928D5D3B9FFD6FFF5EFC69" blockId="11.[145,760,760,965]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1323">
<emphasis id="07950F75FF928D5D3B9FFD6FFE87FCA1" box="[145,257,760,781]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1323">Remarks:</emphasis>
This species is highly troglophilous, and it could represent a strict troglobiont organism, because it has never been collected outside cave systems (
<bibRefCitation id="5170AE96FF928D5D3BF2FCC3FE08FCC5" author="Garcia L" box="[252,398,852,874]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1323" pagination="1 - 4" refId="ref17513" refString="Garcia L. 2020. Algunas observaciones morfologicas sobre Cristarmadillidium breuili Vandel, 1954 (Oniscidea: Armadillidiidae) del Complejo del Arroyo de la Rambla (Peal de Becerro, Jaen). Monografias Bioespeleologicas 15: 1 - 4." type="journal article" year="2020">Garcia, 2020</bibRefCitation>
). However, it does not show any typically troglobious morphological traits other than slight eye and pigment reductions (
<bibRefCitation id="5170AE96FF928D5D395FFC06FF4FFC69" author="Christiansen KA" pageId="11" pageNumber="1323" pagination="517 - 528" refId="ref16935" refString="Christiansen KA. 2012. Morphological adaptations. In: White WB, Culver DC, eds. Encyclopedia of caves, 2 nd edn. Amsterdam: Academic / Elsevier Press, 517 - 528." type="book chapter" year="2012">Christiansen, 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
